121
00:10:06,216 --> 00:10:14,383
[SPEAKER_00]: Something I, well, my career is, when I, my career, when I used to work, there was always something

122
00:10:15,183 --> 00:10:16,304
[SPEAKER_00]: keeps you up at night.

123
00:10:17,545 --> 00:10:24,591
[SPEAKER_00]: As a mayor, what challenges do you see facing the city right now?

124
00:10:24,992 --> 00:10:27,074
[SPEAKER_00]: What keeps you up at night as a mayor?

125
00:10:28,134 --> 00:10:33,676
[SPEAKER_01]: Usually there's a good two to three nights that my eyes are wide open at like 2 or 3 a.m.

126
00:10:33,716 --> 00:10:35,677
[SPEAKER_01]: and then there's nothing that can get me back to sleep.

127
00:10:37,177 --> 00:10:49,081
[SPEAKER_01]: So it's probably what happened during the day, but overall it's affordability for our residents from the transportation to the housing to the food insecurity.

128
00:10:50,322 --> 00:10:52,183
[SPEAKER_01]: making sure our residents have what they need.

129
00:10:52,223 --> 00:10:57,627
[SPEAKER_01]: We do have 42% low income in Medford and I worry about that.

130
00:10:58,688 --> 00:11:13,758
[SPEAKER_01]: I want people to be happy and live the life they deserve to live and when people are worried about bills or the next grocery bill or their heating bill, that's something that causes me a little lack of sleep.

131
00:11:14,899 --> 00:11:18,922
[SPEAKER_01]: Some of the litigation that's going on in the city and how that's transpiring.

132
00:11:21,989 --> 00:11:27,502
[SPEAKER_01]: That sometimes too keeps me up, but it's obviously nothing more than any other mayor is dealing with.

133
00:11:29,039 --> 00:11:32,580
[SPEAKER_01]: Some of it bothers me because it is political, which is unfortunate.

134
00:11:34,020 --> 00:11:34,940
[SPEAKER_01]: So that's another thing.

135
00:11:34,980 --> 00:11:36,801
[SPEAKER_01]: And maybe just personnel matters.

136
00:11:37,081 --> 00:11:44,623
[SPEAKER_01]: When you have to, holding somebody accountable, like I said, that I think builds a better department and person and city is not easy.

137
00:11:44,903 --> 00:11:45,803
[SPEAKER_01]: It's not easy at all.

138
00:11:45,843 --> 00:11:46,843
[SPEAKER_00]: It's a difficult thing.

139
00:11:47,043 --> 00:11:48,264
[SPEAKER_00]: It can be very difficult.

140
00:11:48,304 --> 00:11:49,404
[SPEAKER_01]: Yes.

141
00:11:49,424 --> 00:11:58,646
[SPEAKER_01]: So I try to drive home every night and focus on all the amazing things that we're doing, all the amazing people that work for the city or that volunteer for the city.

142
00:11:59,086 --> 00:12:02,289
[SPEAKER_01]: And I truly do, I name people in my head as I drive home from work.

143
00:12:02,710 --> 00:12:06,313
[SPEAKER_01]: Because my day is, hey mayor, so and so did this.

144
00:12:06,873 --> 00:12:10,016
[SPEAKER_01]: Hey mayor, we gotta do an investigation on this.

145
00:12:10,357 --> 00:12:15,722
[SPEAKER_01]: This person files, it's always a hard day.

146
00:12:15,782 --> 00:12:17,203
[SPEAKER_01]: It can be a hard day.

147
00:12:17,223 --> 00:12:22,928
[SPEAKER_01]: So those are some of the things that keep me up at night.

148
00:12:23,609 --> 00:12:24,410
[SPEAKER_01]: Some of the many, yep.

149
00:12:25,631 --> 00:12:27,632
[SPEAKER_00]: And those are all good reasons, by the way.

150
00:12:27,873 --> 00:12:47,448
[SPEAKER_00]: So, you know, a common concern I hear, and this is people that, you know, a lot of them don't feel that they always know about important decisions or they find out about them after they've already been, you know, made.

151
00:12:48,989 --> 00:12:50,511
[SPEAKER_00]: And I know it's tough to communicate.

152
00:12:50,571 --> 00:12:51,812
[SPEAKER_00]: What would you tell residents?

153
00:12:53,031 --> 00:12:54,873
[SPEAKER_00]: You know, that want to be more plugged in.

154
00:12:54,893 --> 00:13:00,878
[SPEAKER_00]: You know, what's the best way to really stay on top of what's happening, or is there a good way?

155
00:13:00,898 --> 00:13:01,218
[SPEAKER_01]: Sure, sure.

156
00:13:01,338 --> 00:13:09,285
[SPEAKER_01]: You know, we have a great comms director, and we have a communications specialist, and they're both full-time working hard to get communication out.

157
00:13:10,212 --> 00:13:25,698
[SPEAKER_01]: The first thing I probably would say is that you need to, some people just go online and are on Facebook or social media saying, we didn't know about this, we didn't know about this, we didn't know about this, but take even five minutes to sign up for our newsletter.

158
00:13:25,858 --> 00:13:28,259
[SPEAKER_01]: We put out a newsletter monthly.

159
00:13:29,079 --> 00:13:31,660
[SPEAKER_01]: Or sign up for our robocall system.

160
00:13:31,920 --> 00:13:36,622
[SPEAKER_01]: It can be a phone call, it can be, you get text messages, or emails.

161
00:13:37,542 --> 00:13:38,143
[SPEAKER_01]: All of the above.

162
00:13:38,223 --> 00:13:40,624
[SPEAKER_01]: I get all of the above, so I know they all went out.

163
00:13:40,985 --> 00:13:43,267
[SPEAKER_01]: And those are important communication.

164
00:13:43,327 --> 00:13:51,293
[SPEAKER_01]: It's an important communication tool that goes out to thousands, tells you about events, tells you about important meetings, reminds you to check the website.

165
00:13:51,913 --> 00:13:55,476
[SPEAKER_01]: We're trying to remind people of the communication pieces.

166
00:13:56,297 --> 00:13:58,258
[SPEAKER_01]: Then we also have two social media pages.

167
00:13:58,338 --> 00:14:03,182
[SPEAKER_01]: We have the City of Medford social media page that we're pushing out information daily.

168
00:14:04,370 --> 00:14:08,280
[SPEAKER_01]: as well as my mayor page on social media.

169
00:14:08,761 --> 00:14:13,673
[SPEAKER_01]: So those are some of the ways they can actually sign up and

170
00:14:14,813 --> 00:14:19,397
[SPEAKER_01]: or like a Facebook page and get to the second communications.

171
00:14:20,018 --> 00:14:30,267
[SPEAKER_01]: We also are starting this, because I do hear it a lot too, some people say I didn't know about that meeting and we will talk in my office, we robocalled it out twice.

172
00:14:31,689 --> 00:14:34,491
[SPEAKER_01]: It's on the school and the city website calendar.

173
00:14:35,232 --> 00:14:37,293
[SPEAKER_01]: So checking the calendars, too, is very important.

174
00:14:37,574 --> 00:14:41,876
[SPEAKER_01]: Everything is on that monthly calendar, and you'll know, oh, in two weeks, there's a zoning meeting.

175
00:14:42,196 --> 00:14:45,999
[SPEAKER_01]: There's a building committee meeting for the new school.

176
00:14:46,239 --> 00:14:47,079
[SPEAKER_01]: Let me get involved.

177
00:14:47,480 --> 00:14:50,241
[SPEAKER_01]: We also try to do surveys because we know people are very busy.

178
00:14:50,301 --> 00:14:54,664
[SPEAKER_01]: They sometimes don't even have time, never mind to watch a meeting, but to read an email.

179
00:14:55,024 --> 00:15:00,067
[SPEAKER_01]: So doing a survey on your own time, we do try to get input through that avenue.

180
00:15:00,888 --> 00:15:04,030
[SPEAKER_01]: We also are creating a neighborhood liaison committee

